# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: some-ip
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] These standards are specified in Clauses 125 and 126 of the IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The physical (PHY) layer transmission technology of IEEE 802.3bz is based on 10GBASE-T, but operates at a lower signaling rate.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] By reducing the original signal rate to 1⁄4 or 1⁄2, the link speed drops to 2.5 or 5 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The spectral bandwidth of the signal is reduced accordingly, lowering the requirements on the cabling, so that 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T can be deployed at a cable length of up to 100 m on Cat 5e or better cables.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The NBASE-T effort also standardized how its switches can implement power over Ethernet according to the IEEE 802.3at and successor standards.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] This allows a single cable to provide both power and data for high-bandwidth wireless access points such as those that implement the IEEE 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standards.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Prior to the release of 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T, manufacturers of wireless access points that wanted to support multi-gigabit uplink speed using standard gigabit Ethernet ports had to include multiple Ethernet ports on their access points.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] By bonding the connections from multiple Ethernet ports via IEEE 802.3ad link aggregation or similar, manufacturers were able to achieve speeds close to 2 Gbit/s by using two ports that support gigabit speeds.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] This would require the wireless access point to be connected to the rest of the network with 2 Ethernet cables and require both the wireless access point and network hardware to support and be configured for link aggregation.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Wireless access points that support 2.5GBASE-T or 5GBASE-T eliminate this complexity.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] In 2013 with the release of IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5), wireless access points for the first time could reach speeds of 2 Gbit/s or 4 Gbit/s, exceeding the 1 Gbit/s IEEE 802.3ab 1000BASE-T wired Ethernet uplink.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] While 10GBASE-T had already been standardized since 2006, this standard used a higher signaling frequency that would have substantially limited the maximum distance of Cat5e cable runs.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Therefore, there was demand for an intermediate standard that could uplink the 2 Gbit/s and 4 Gbit/s speeds from wireless access points over existing Cat5e cable.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The development of the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards enabled wireless access points to reach their maximum speeds without being limited by the Ethernet uplink speeds over a single existing Cat5e cable, while also being compatible with newer Cat6 and Cat6a cabling.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards also serve as an interim solution for achieving lower-cost and lower power consumption multi-gigabit network speeds.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] As of Dec 2022, 10GBASE-T network equipment is still substantially more expensive than 1GBASE-T, 2.5GBASE-T, and 5GBASE-T network equipment.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3bz also supports power over Ethernet, which had previously not been available with IEEE 802.3an 10GBASE-T.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] As early as 2013, the Intel Avoton server processors integrated 2.5 Gbit/s Ethernet ports.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Whilst Broadcom had announced a series of 2.5 Gbit/s transceiver ICs, 2.5 Gbit/s switch hardware was not widely commercially available at that point.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Many early 10GBASE-T switches, particularly those with SFP+ interfaces, do not support the intermediate speeds.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] In October 2014, the NBASE-T Alliance was founded, initially comprising Cisco, Aquantia, Freescale, and Xilinx.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] By December 2015, it contained more than 45 companies, and aimed to have its specification compatible with 802.3bz.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The competing MGBASE-T Alliance, stating the same faster Gigabit Ethernet objectives, was founded in December 2014.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] In contrast to NBASE-T, the MGBASE-T said that their specifications would be open source.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3's 2.5G/5GBASE-T Task Force started working on the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards in March 2015.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The two NBASE-T and MGBASE-T Alliances ended up collaborating. with the forming of the IEEE 802.3bz Task Force under the patronage of the Ethernet Alliance in June 2015.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] On September 23, 2016, the IEEE-SA Standards Board approved IEEE Std 802.3bz-2016.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3ch-2020 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 standards are derived from the IEEE 802.3bp-2016 1000BASE-T1 Ethernet over single twisted pair standard, and share very little in common with the similarly named 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards at the PHY layer.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 can run over a single twisted pair up to 15 meters in length, use PAM8 modulation (compared to PAM3 modulation in 1000BASE-T1 or PAM-16 + 128DSQ in 2.5GBASE-T/5GBASE-T), and are standardized in 802.3ch-2020.
[src:some-ip/automotive-ethernet] Their primary use is in embedded automotive applications, and are commonly referred to as part of the Automotive Ethernet family of standards, along with 100BASE-T1 and 1000BASE-T1.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The objectives are scalability to different vehicle and platform variants, transferability of software, consideration of availability and safety requirements, cooperation between different partners, sustainable use of natural resources and maintainability during the product lifecycle.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR was formed in July 2003 by Bavarian Motor Works (BMW), Robert Bosch GmbH, Continental AG, Mercedes-Benz Group AG, Siemens VDO and Volkswagen AG to develop and establish an open industry standard for the automotive electrical-electronic (E/E) architecture.
[src:some-ip/autosar] In November 2003, the Ford Motor Company joined as a Core Partner.
[src:some-ip/autosar] In the following December Peugeot Citroën Automobiles S.A. and the Toyota Motor Corporation followed.
[src:some-ip/autosar] In November of the following year, General Motors Holding LLC also joined as a Core Partner.
[src:some-ip/autosar] After Siemens VDO was acquired by Continental in February 2008, Siemens VDO is no longer independently represented as a Core Partner of AUTOSAR.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Since 2003, AUTOSAR has provided four major versions of the standardized automotive software architecture for its Classic Platform and one release, along with the version of acceptance tests.
[src:some-ip/autosar] In 2013, the AUTOSAR consortium introduced a continuous working mode for the Classic Platform to maintain the standard and provide selected improvements (including releases R4.2, and 1.0 of acceptance tests).
[src:some-ip/autosar] In 2016, work began on the Adaptive Platform.
[src:some-ip/autosar] An initial release (17-03) was published in early 2017, followed by release 17–10 in October 2017 and release 18–03 in March 2018.
[src:some-ip/autosar] With release 18–10 in October 2018, the major development activities were published.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR aims to establish a global standard for software and methodology, enabling open E/E system architectures for future intelligent mobility.
[src:some-ip/autosar] This vision focuses on ensuring high levels of dependability, particularly in terms of safety and security.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR provides specifications for basic software modules, defines application interfaces, and builds a common development methodology based on a standardized exchange format.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The basic software modules made available by the AUTOSAR layered software architecture can be used in vehicles from different manufacturers and electronic components from different suppliers, thereby reducing expenditures for research and development.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Based on this principle, AUTOSAR aims to prepare for upcoming technologies.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The motivation behind AUTOSAR is to manage the increasing complexity of software and E/E systems as their functional scope expands.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The initiative is designed to support flexibility in product modifications, upgrades, and updates, while leveraging scalable solutions within and across product lines.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Enhancing scalability and flexibility in the integration and transfer of functions is a key objective, aiming to improve the quality and reliability of software and E/E systems.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The goals of AUTOSAR include addressing future vehicle requirements such as availability, safety, software upgrades, updates, and maintainability.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR seeks to enhance scalability and flexibility for function integration and transfer.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Additionally, the initiative aims to increase the use of "Commercial off the Shelf" software and hardware components across product lines, promoting software reuse.
[src:some-ip/autosar] By accelerating development and maintenance processes, AUTOSAR intends to improve the management of product and process complexity and risk, while optimizing the costs associated with scalable systems.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The purpose of the foundation standard is to enforce interoperability between the AUTOSAR platforms.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The foundation contains common requirements and technical specifications (for example protocols) shared between the AUTOSAR platforms, and the common methodology.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The AUTOSAR classic platform is the standard for embedded real-time ECUs based on OSEK.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The architecture distinguishes between three software layers that run on a microcontroller: application, runtime environment (RTE) and basic software (BSW).
[src:some-ip/autosar] The application software layer is mostly hardware independent.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Communication between software components and access to BSW happens via RTE, which represents the full interface for applications.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Services are divided further, into functional groups representing the infrastructure for system, memory and communication services.
[src:some-ip/autosar] One essential concept of the Classic Platform is the Virtual Functional Bus (VFB).
[src:some-ip/autosar] This virtual bus is an abstract set of RTEs that are not yet deployed to specific ECUs and decouples the applications from the infrastructure.
[src:some-ip/autosar] It communicates via dedicated ports, which means that the communication interfaces of the application software must be mapped to these ports.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The VFB handles communication within the individual ECU and between ECUs.
[src:some-ip/autosar] From an application point of view, no detailed knowledge of lower-level technologies or dependencies is required.
[src:some-ip/autosar] This supports hardware-independent development and usage of application software.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The Classic Platform also enables the integration of non-AUTOSAR systems such as GENIVI, now renamed COVESA, by using the Franca Interface Definition Language (Franca IDL).
[src:some-ip/autosar] Standardization of functional interfaces across manufacturers and suppliers and standardization of the interfaces between the different software layers is seen as a basis for achieving the technical goals of AUTOSAR.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Only by standardizing concrete interface contents in their physical and temporal representation allows achieving the needed integration compatibility.
[src:some-ip/autosar] New use-cases required the development of the adaptive platform.
[src:some-ip/autosar] One example is automated driving, in the context of which the driver temporarily and/or partially transfers responsibility for driving to the vehicle.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Further, Car-2-X applications require interaction to vehicles and off-board systems.
[src:some-ip/autosar] That means that the system has to provide secure on-board communication, support of cross-domain computing platforms, smartphone integration, integration of non-AUTOSAR systems, and so on.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Also, cloud-based services will require dedicated means for security, such as secure cloud interaction and emergency vehicle preemption.
[src:some-ip/autosar] They will enable remote and distributed services, such as remote diagnostics, over the air (OTA) update, repair, and exchange handling.
[src:some-ip/autosar] To support dynamic deployment of customer applications and to provide an environment for applications that require high-end computing power AUTOSAR is currently standardizing the AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Its core is an operating system based on the POSIX standard.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The operating system can be used by the application via a subset of the POSIX according to IEEE1003.13 (namely PSE51).
[src:some-ip/autosar] One of the key features of the Adaptive Platform is service-oriented communication since the Platform is based on the Service - Oriented Architecture.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Adaptive AUTOSAR is developed and written using C++ which is an object-oriented programming language.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The communication protocol used for the in-vehicle networking is SOME/IP, based on Ethernet.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Two types of interfaces are available: services and application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:some-ip/autosar] The platform consists of functional clusters which are grouped in services and the AUTOSAR adaptive platform foundation.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Functional clusters in AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform have to have at least one instance per (virtual) machine while services may be distributed in the in-car network.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The adaptive platform contains both specification and code.
[src:some-ip/autosar] In comparison to the Classic Platform, AUTOSAR develops an implementation to shorten the validation cycle and illustrate the underlying concepts.
[src:some-ip/autosar] This implementation is available to all AUTOSAR partners.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR defined six different levels of membership.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Core Partners are since 2026 AUMOVIO (AUMOVIO Germany GmbH), BMW (BMW AG), Bosch (Robert Bosch GmbH), Denso, GM (General Motors Holding LLC), Huawei (Huawei Technologies Co.Ltd.), Mercedes-Benz (Mercedes-Benz Group AG), Toyota (TMC), Vector (Vector Informatik GmbH) and VW (Volkswagen AG).
[src:some-ip/autosar] These companies are responsible for organization, administration and control of the AUTOSAR development partnership.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Within this core, the executive board defines the overall strategy and roadmap.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The Steering Committee manages day-to-day non-technical operations and admission of partners, public relations and contractual issues.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The chairman and Deputy of chairman, appointed for one year, represent the Steering Committee for that purpose.
[src:some-ip/autosar] The AUTOSAR Spokesperson takes over the communication with the outside world.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Premium Partner Plus companies support the project leader team in the various technical, organizational and everyday processes.
[src:some-ip/autosar] They also give new strategic inputs to the project leader round.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Premium and Development members contribute to work packages coordinated and monitored by the Project Leader Team established by the Core Partners.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Associate partners are making use of the standard documents AUTOSAR has already released.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Attendees are currently participating with Academic collaboration and non-commercial projects.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Selection of vendors, including RTOS, BSW, design tools, compiler, etc.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Vendors which provide related tools and software, e.g. for testing, diagnostics, development, etc.
[src:some-ip/autosar] AUTOSAR takes part in various events every year.
[src:some-ip/autosar] Furthermore the AUTOSAR Open Conference (AOC) is planned every year to network and give an overview over the newest achievements.
[src:some-ip/autosar] A list of the events which are planned can be found on the AUTOSAR website.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:some-ip/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:some-ip/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:some-ip/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:some-ip/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:some-ip/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:some-ip/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:some-ip/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:some-ip/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:some-ip/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:some-ip/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
